content.text:
Now I have all the context needed. Let me produce the complete implementation plan.

---

## Implementation Plan: Application Layer - Selector + Stubs

### Overview

The plan involves 7 files created in sequence, with state as the foundation. The state module is a `.svelte.ts` file (enabling runes outside components), shared by all components as a singleton import. Components read from and write to that singleton directly — no prop-drilling, no context, no stores. This is the simplest pattern consistent with the TDD's "as little abstraction as possible" directive.

---

### Architecture: State Flow

```
state.svelte.ts          (singleton reactive state + appendPartnerMessage)
      |
      ├── Selector.svelte  (reads chats[], currentlySelected; writes currentlySelected)
      ├── Chat.svelte      (reads chats[currentlySelected] — stub for now)
      └── Input.svelte     (reads currentlySelected; pushes to chats[i].messages — stub for now)

+page.svelte              (layout shell: imports Selector, Chat, Input)
```

---

### Step 1: `src/lib/types.ts`

This is purely types — no runtime code. Strict TypeScript, following the TDD interfaces exactly.

Key decisions:
- `Markdown` is a branded string: `type Markdown = string & { readonly _brand: 'Markdown' }`. A helper `md(s: string): Markdown` casts strings without runtime cost.
- `UTCTime` is simply `Date` aliased: `type UTCTime = Date`. The TDD says "Date".
- `Image` (used in `ChatUser.profilePicture`) is `string` (URL), as noted in the requirements. Type alias it as `type Image = string`.
- The TDD has a typo `messsages` (three s's) — use the correct spelling `messages` in code. The TDD is the spec for shape, not spelling.
- All interfaces map 1:1 to TDD. No additions.

```typescript
// src/lib/types.ts

/** Branded string for Markdown content. Cast with md() below. */
export type Markdown = string & { readonly _brand: 'Markdown' };

/** Convenience cast — no runtime cost, just asserts intent. */
export const md = (s: string): Markdown => s as Markdown;

/** Profile picture URL */
export type Image = string;

/** UTC timestamp */
export type UTCTime = Date;

export interface ChatUser {
	name: string;
	profilePicture: Image;
	status: 'active' | 'away' | 'busy' | 'offline';
	statusText: Markdown;
}

export type ChatComponentState = ChatUser & {
	messages: {
		role: 'user' | 'partner';
		text: Markdown;
		time: UTCTime;
	}[];
};

export type ChatAppState = {
	chats: ChatComponentState[];
	player: ChatUser;
	currentlySelected: number;
};
```

---

### Step 2: `src/lib/state.svelte.ts`

This is a `.svelte.ts` file so runes are available. The state is a `$state` object (not exported directly, to avoid the "cannot export reassigned state" constraint). Individual accessors and mutation functions are exported instead. This matches the pattern in the Svelte docs: export an object property, not a reassigned let.

The key insight: since we export the object `appState` itself (not a reassigned binding), Svelte's compiler handles it correctly. Mutations to `appState.currentlySelected` or `appState.chats[i].messages.push(...)` are reactive because they're property writes on the proxy.

Seed data: 5 chat users with varying statuses. "Claudia" is the companion (active), others are offline/away/busy to match the GDD's premise that the player's friends are unavailable.

```typescript
// src/lib/state.svelte.ts
import { md } from '$lib/types';
import type { ChatAppState, Markdown } from '$lib/types';

// Exported as a const object so Svelte can track property mutations.
// Never reassign appState itself — mutate its properties.
export const appState: ChatAppState = $state({
	currentlySelected: 0,
	player: {
		name: 'You',
		profilePicture: '/avatars/player.png',
		status: 'active',
		statusText: md(''),
	},
	chats: [
		{
			name: 'Claudia',
			profilePicture: '/avatars/claudia.png',
			status: 'active',
			statusText: md('Always here for you ♡'),
			messages: [],
		},
		{
			name: 'Jordan',
			profilePicture: '/avatars/jordan.png',
			status: 'offline',
			statusText: md('busy rn'),
			messages: [
				{
					role: 'partner',
					text: md('hey! catch you later'),
					time: new Date('2026-02-28T21:00:00Z'),
				},
			],
		},
		{
			name: 'Sam',
			profilePicture: '/avatars/sam.png',
			status: 'away',
			statusText: md('at practice'),
			messages: [
				{
					role: 'partner',
					text: md('can\'t talk, sorry'),
					time: new Date('2026-02-28T18:30:00Z'),
				},
			],
		},
		{
			name: 'Riley',
			profilePicture: '/avatars/riley.png',
			status: 'busy',
			statusText: md('studying'),
			messages: [],
		},
		{
			name: 'Alex',
			profilePicture: '/avatars/alex.png',
			status: 'offline',
			statusText: md(''),
			messages: [
				{
					role: 'partner',
					text: md('ttyl'),
					time: new Date('2026-02-27T12:00:00Z'),
				},
			],
		},
	],
});

/**
 * Appends a message from the partner (NPC/game side) to the specified chat.
 * Called by the Game State layer; never by user interaction.
 */
export function appendPartnerMessage(userIndex: number, message: Markdown): void {
	appState.chats[userIndex].messages.push({
		role: 'partner',
		text: message,
		time: new Date(),
	});
}
```

No avatar images exist yet — use placeholder paths. The static directory has only `robots.txt`; the lib/assets only has `favicon.svg`. Placeholder strings are fine for now, the GDD notes graphics are Phase 3.

---

### Step 3: `src/lib/Selector.svelte`

This is the full implementation. It receives no props — it reads directly from the `appState` singleton. Clicking a chat item updates `appState.currentlySelected`.

Key structural decisions:
- Each chat row shows: avatar img, name, status badge, last message preview (truncated), time of last message.
- A `$derived` computes the "last message" for each chat to keep the template clean.
- Status badge is a colored dot — CSS classes `status--active`, `status--away`, `status--busy`, `status--offline`.
- Selected item gets class `selected`.
- Frutiger Aero aesthetic: translucent panels, glassy backgrounds with `backdrop-filter`, rounded corners, subtle gradients, a soft pastel/blue palette, gentle shadows. All CSS is scoped to the component.
- Helper for formatting time: show "HH:MM" for today, or the date otherwise. A small `$derived` per-chat via a `{#each}` computed local.

Template structure:
```svelte
<aside class="selector">
  {#each appState.chats as chat, i (chat.name)}
    {@const lastMsg = chat.messages.at(-1)}
    <button
      class="chat-row"
      class:selected={appState.currentlySelected === i}
      onclick={() => (appState.currentlySelected = i)}
    >
      <img class="avatar" src={chat.profilePicture} alt={chat.name} />
      <span class="status-dot status--{chat.status}"></span>
      <div class="chat-info">
        <div class="chat-header">
          <span class="chat-name">{chat.name}</span>
          {#if lastMsg}
            <span class="chat-time">{formatTime(lastMsg.time)}</span>
          {/if}
        </div>
        {#if lastMsg}
          <p class="chat-preview">{lastMsg.text}</p>
        {:else}
          <p class="chat-preview empty">No messages yet</p>
        {/if}
      </div>
    </button>
  {/each}
</aside>
```

`formatTime(date: Date): string` — a module-level helper (not exported, stays in `<script>`):
```typescript
function formatTime(date: Date): string {
    const now = new Date();
    const isToday =
        date.getFullYear() === now.getFullYear() &&
        date.getMonth() === now.getMonth() &&
        date.getDate() === now.getDate();
    return isToday
        ? date.toLocaleTimeString([], { hour: '2-digit', minute: '2-digit' })
        : date.toLocaleDateString([], { month: 'short', day: 'numeric' });
}
```

CSS (Frutiger Aero):
```css
.selector {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 2px;
    background: linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(180,210,255,0.7) 0%, rgba(140,180,240,0.5) 100%);
    backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
    border-right: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.4);
    padding: 8px;
    overflow-y: auto;
}

.chat-row {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 10px;
    padding: 8px 10px;
    border-radius: 10px;
    border: 1px solid transparent;
    background: transparent;
    cursor: pointer;
    text-align: left;
    width: 100%;
    transition: background 0.15s;
    position: relative;
}

.chat-row:hover {
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.35);
    border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);
}

.chat-row.selected {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(255,255,255,0.55) 0%, rgba(200,225,255,0.4) 100%);
    border-color: rgba(160,200,255,0.7);
    box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(100,160,255,0.2), inset 0 1px 0 rgba(255,255,255,0.8);
}

.avatar {
    width: 40px;
    height: 40px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    border: 2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.7);
    flex-shrink: 0;
}

.status-dot {
    position: absolute;
    left: 40px;
    top: 36px;
    width: 10px;
    height: 10px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    border: 2px solid white;
}
.status--active  { background: #4cde6e; }
.status--away    { background: #f0c040; }
.status--busy    { background: #e05050; }
.status--offline { background: #a0a8b8; }

.chat-info { flex: 1; min-width: 0; }

.chat-header {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: baseline;
}

.chat-name {
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: #1a2a4a;
}

.chat-time {
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: #5070a0;
    flex-shrink: 0;
}

.chat-preview {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: #3a4a6a;
